🔍 Step 6 — STL preflight check before every print
Before you slice anything, run a quick printability check on the model:

python
# Install the requests library
pip install requests

# preflight_check.py — drop your STL URL in here
import requests

def check_printability(stl_url):
    resp = requests.post(
        "https://api.meshy.ai/openapi/v1/3d-model/analyze-printability",
        json={"model_url": stl_url},
        headers={"Authorization": "Bearer YOUR_MESHY_API_KEY"}
    )
    result = resp.json()
    print("Printability result:", result)
    return result

# Example usage
check_printability("https://yourfile.com/model.stl")
Meshy API is free for printability checks — sign up at meshy.ai to get your API key

This catches:

Non-manifold (broken) geometry

Holes in the mesh

Extremely thin walls

Degenerate faces

If it fails, fix the model in Meshmixer or PrusaSlicer's repair tool before slicing.

🧩 Step 7 — Slicer setup for Kobra X
Use OrcaSlicer — it's free, open-source, and has the most accurate Kobra X profiles:

Download: github.com/SoftFever/OrcaSlicer

Safe starting profile for Kobra X + PLA:

Setting	Value
Layer height	0.2 mm
Print speed	150 mm/s max
First layer speed	30 mm/s
Infill	15% gyroid
Supports	Tree (auto)
Bed temp	60°C + 30 min heat soak
Nozzle temp	215°C
Cooling	100% from layer 3
Z-offset	Tune with paper test
The golden rule: run a first layer calibration before every new filament spool. Don't skip this.

🔁 Step 8 — Print log (track every job)
Add a tiny SQLite log so you know what worked and what didn't, and can spot patterns:

python
# print_log.py
import sqlite3
from datetime import datetime

conn = sqlite3.connect("print_history.db")
conn.execute("""
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS prints (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
    date TEXT,
    model TEXT,
    filament TEXT,
    profile TEXT,
    duration_mins INTEGER,
    result TEXT,    -- 'success', 'failure', 'paused'
    failure_type TEXT,  -- 'spaghetti', 'adhesion', 'warp', etc.
    notes TEXT
)
""")

def log_print(model, filament, profile, duration, result, failure_type="", notes=""):
    conn.execute(
        "INSERT INTO prints VALUES (NULL,?,?,?,?,?,?,?,?)",
        (datetime.now().isoformat(), model, filament, profile, duration, result, failure_type, notes)
    )
    conn.commit()
    print(f"✅ Logged: {model} — {result}")

# Example
log_print("benchy.stl", "PLA Hatchbox White", "KobraX_PLA_safe", 90, "success")
Run this after every print — even if it's just 30 seconds of effort. After 20–30 prints you'll have a goldmine of data to spot patterns and tune further.

